<topic class="Popup" template="Default" status="Under Construction" modified="2022-03-21T14:18:55.226Z" lasteditedby="Adam" version="2" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation="../../../helpproject.xsd">
  <title>Degrees-of-Freedom</title>
  <keywords>
    <keyword>Definition<keyword>Degrees-of-Freedom</keyword><keyword>DOF</keyword></keyword>
  </keywords>
  <body>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><table styleclass="PopupTable" rowcount="1" colcount="1">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">The <text styleclass="Interface">Degrees-of-Freedom</text> of a kinematic-chain has a number of definitions. The definitions are closely related, and include:</para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">1: Number of independent coordinates that are needed to define the position of the element/mechanism...</para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">- or -</para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">2: The number of parameters needed to find unambiguously the geometry configuration of a system in space</para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">- or -</para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">3: The number of inputs needed to obtain a predictable output of a mechanism</para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">- or -</para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">4: The number of independent ways a kinematic-chain can move, or the number of independent coordinates or dimensions that you need to define its position.</para>
          <para styleclass="Normal"><line style="height:1px; color:#993300;" /></para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">You can use the Gruebler Equation to calculate the number of Degrees-of-Freedom of each kinematic-chain.</para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">The Kutzbach Criterion states that for a kinematic-chain to be useful, the number of &apos;drives&apos; (inputs) must equal the number of degree-of-freedom. In <text styleclass="VariableName-IT" style="font-size:10pt;">MechDesigner</text>, we use a Motion-Dimensions as a &apos;Drive&apos; (input) for each degrees-of-freedom.</para>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table></para>
  </body>
</topic>
